	<a id="c87485782"></a>
	<div class="comment" id="comment-87485782">
		<div class="comment-content">
			<p>Here is another solution: Gmail.</p>

<p>Note: while I admit I am a convert to Gmail, and therefore biased, the big feature for me is in fact search (I also like the tagging). The big downside is off-line access, but Gmail does support POP and rumour has it that they might add IMAP support.  Of course, once off-line you are back to Outlook or Thunderbird or (pick your client)...</p>
		</div>
		<p class="comment-footer">
			Posted by:
			<a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="http://www.paymentswatch.com" href="http://www.typepad.com/t/comments?__mode=red&amp;user_id=2419952&amp;id=87485782">John Januszczak</a> |
			<a href="http://www.iunknown.com/2007/10/outlook-2007-se.html#comment-87485782">October 24, 2007 at 07:37 AM</a>
		</p>
	</div>
	<a id="c87489520"></a>
	<div class="comment" id="comment-87489520">
		<div class="comment-content">
			<p>I use Gmail all the time for mail that gets routed to my iunknown.com address. However, for managing the 10X greater volume of mail that I have at work, Outlook is quite a nice solution (especially now that I've added the 3 essential macros that I need to fit my workflow).</p>
		</div>
